kv.description: (http://www.http://asso-base.fr/sites/asso-base.fr/IMG/pdf/Jay_Fuhrer.pdf) is a slideshow by Jay Fuhrer that reports on Gabe Brown's use of cover crop cocktails and grazing to increase profits as well as soil health in a 16-inch rainfall zone. Gabe Brown has been using no-till since 1991, and in 2006 began seeding cover crops after grain harvest consisting of 15 or more species, which he then fall grazes with his cow herd. By combining cropping with grazing, the Browns (http://bcscd.com/?id=53) have reduced fertilizer use by 90% and herbicide use by 75%, increased the rate of water infiltration many times, and more than doubled their soil organic matter in the top foot of soil, most of which they attribute to the combination of cover cropping and grazing/trampling and their active soil biology.
kv.label1: percent organic matter 1991, 0-6-inch depth

kv.description: This post was put in to bedrock in 1923, in deep peat or muck soils. The top was level with the soil surface. Due to drainage and subsequent oxidation of these peat soils, the surface has subsided more than 1.5 m since 1923. In 1927 this area was drained for sugarcane production, and the loss of soil C has been estimated at 20 T C per hectare per year, assuming a bulk density of .22 and a carbon content of .11 g per cubic centimeter. (http://www.hos.ufl.edu/vegetarian/09/Nov/Soil%20Subsidence%20in%20the%20Everglades%20Agricultural%20Area.pdf) Soil subsidence in the Everglades area (http://www.grist.org/i/assets/notill_and_C_sequestration.pdf) Agriculture, Ecosystems and Environment 118 (2007) 1-5
kv.label1: cm of peat per year

kv.description: The 2002 Biscuit Fire in southwest Oregon burned 200,000 hectares, including some soil research plots. After the fire, Forest Service scientists analyzed the soil layers in the plots, and documented an astounding loss of soil carbon and nitrogen, not only from the surface layer of organic matter, but in the mineral soil layers, where a majority of the losses occurred. An inch of soil, about 127 tons per hectare, disappeared, perhaps into the smoke plume, leaving a crust of rocks behind. The loss of topsoil, carbon, and nitrogen from soil can negatively affect a range of processes, including nutrient retention and water infiltration. In the absence of nitrogen-fixing plants, such losses of nitrogen would require at least a century to be reversed, according to the researchers. Wildfire (http://asd-www.larc.nasa.gov/biomass_burn/globe_impact.html) may contribute to climate change in the short term, by releasing carbon and nitrous oxide as greenhouse gases and, in the long term, by reducing soil productivity through losses of organic matter and nutrients. With less productive soils, a forest will not grow as quickly nor reabsorb as much carbon as before a burn. (http://rparticle.web-p.cisti.nrc.ca/rparticle/AbstractTemplateServlet?calyLang=eng&journal=cjfr&volume=38&year=0&issue=11&msno=x08-136) Can. J. For. Res. 38(11): 2771-83 (2008)
kv.label1: tons C per hectare

kv.description: The Blackstone Ranch (headquartered in Ranchos de Taos, New Mexico) reported a spectacular 1-year gain in average organic matter from 2008 to 2009, from 6% organic matter to 9.45% on its irrigated pastures, according to test results from New Mexico State University reported in (http://holisticmanagement.org) Holistic Management International's journal, In Practice (March/April 2010). In the pasture pictured in 2008, 50% of the ground was bare, with an average distance from a random dart to a perennial grass of 8.54 inches. Managers increased stock density by 220%. This is the degree of concentration of cattle, which gives better recovery periods for the grass and more concentrated trampling, dunging, and urinating. There was an estimated 300% increase in production over the whole grazing operation. In 2009, the pasture pictured had only 38% bare ground, with only 2.1 inches from the random dart to a perennial grass plant.
kv.label1: percent increase in organic matter per year, in top few inches

kv.description: The Questa pasture of the Blackstone Ranch (headquartered in Ranchos de Taos, New Mexico) reported a spectacular 1-year gain in average organic matter from 2008 to 2009, from 1% organic matter to 1.9%, according to test results from New Mexico State University reported in (http://holisticmanagement.org) Holistic Management International's journal, In Practice (March/April 2010). Soil surface monitoring showed that during the same period, plant spacing decreased from 3.51 inches to 2.92 inches, approximately a 25% decrease in bare ground. Managers increased stock density by 220%. This is the degree of concentration of cattle, which gives better recovery periods for the grass as well as increased trampling, dunging, urinating during a shorter period. There was an estimated 300% increase in production over the whole grazing operation.
kv.label1: percent increase in organic matter per year, in top few inches

kv.description: Long-term experiment, 1992-2005, at Book Book, south of Wagga Wagga in NSW on annual and perennial pastures, limed and unlimed. Limed perennial pastures gained the most soil carbon, but others also gained significant soil carbon. 'Our results suggest that pasture holds the key to maintaining, and even increasing, SOC [soil organic carbon] under crop/pasture in this environment.' Soil carbon dynamics under different cropping and pasture management in temperate Australia: Results of three long-term experiments. Soil Research, 2011, 49, 320-328.

kv.description: The Breton Plots near Breton, Alberta were established in 1929 by the Soils Department of the University of Alberta to find a farming system that was adapted to the region. (http://soil.scijournals.org/cgi/reprint/65/2/431) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J. 65:431-441 (2001) reports that some plots in a wheat-oat-barley-hay-hay rotation, with additions of manure, gained 17 tons organic C per ha in the sampled plow layer (15 cm), based on analysis of archived samples from 1938 and resampling in 1990, or .33 T C per ha per yr.

kv.description: A 10-year study at the University of California, Davis monitored soil C gain and the rate of conversion of organic inputs to soil organic carbon. The highest rate of carbon accrual that they recorded was with an organic corn/tomato rotation, with external C inputs from composted manure. For the entire study, the conversion of crop residue carbon to soil carbon was 7.6%. (http://soil.scijournals.org/cgi/reprint/69/4/1078) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J. 69:1078-1085 (2005)

kv.description: Kenneth Olson at the University of Illinois measured soil organic carbon change from 3 tillage methods over 20 years in an alternate corn-soybean rotation on a 6% slope with silt loam. Over 20 years, down to 75 cm, the moldboard plow treatment lost 15.2 tons C per ha, the chisel plow treatment lost 15.1, and the no-till 6.8 tons C per ha. See Tillage, Slope, and Erosion Effects on SOC, Soil Science 175, No. 11, November 2010, and Soil organic carbon sequestration, storage, retention, and loss in U.S. croplands: Issues paper for protocol development, Geoderma 196-96 (2013) 201-206.

kv.description: (http://www.ars.usda.gov/SP2UserFiles/Place/66120900/SoilManagementAndCarbonSequestration/2009ajfJ04-Soil-profileCandNduring12years-AGEE12928.pdf) Agriculture, Ecosystems and Environment 129 (2009) 28-36 reports that a 12-year study by the Agricultural Research Service (Alan Franzluebbers) showed significant gains in soil organic carbon under continuous season-long grazing of a Bermuda grass pasture with a stocking rate of 5.8 500-lb. steers per hectare (14.3 per acre). Some pastures were fertilized with inorganic nitrogen, others with broiler litter. Soil organic carbon concentrations were greatest within 5 meters of shade and water. Ungrazed, unharvested pasture plots gained .64 tons C per hectare per year, those with high grazing pressure (8.7 steers per hectare) .51 tons C per hectare per year, and hayed plots lost .22 tons C per hectare per year. Below 30 cm depth, soil carbon losses over the 12-year study period were common.
kv.label1: tons C per ha per yr in top 90 cm

kv.description: The property is covered with native pastures which have not been improved and in fact were previously stripped bare to the ground for most of its life by poor farming practices in the past. Five years ago it was decided that a new way must be achieved for the property to become profitable. After receiving a government grant we put in place a Rotational Grazing project on our farm with other farms also being involved on their projects, and the Carbon Soils Group was launched. Our individual project was based upon leaving a min. of 1500 Kg/ha of Dry Matter (DM) in all paddocks to allow water retention and give the grasses the ability to regenerate quickly above and below ground. The paddocks were subdivided into 10-20ha sizes with a single electric fences divisions and hot tap gates.This was done during a drought period using the same number of cattle for the entire project. As a result there was more grass available to the cattle than under fixed stocking rates of the past due to the fact the grasses were never grazed down to ground level and were never grazed sooner than 60 days, and preferably 90 days in the rotation. Over the coming years other native grasses started to germinate which have not been seen previously, the paddocks became thicker in growth, and there was always fresh new green growth available to the cattle in the next cell rotation, even in drought. As a result, more organic matter was reconstituted into the ground over the 4 years of the project, through manure and the grasses themselves which increased the carbon levels and with the added benefit of healthier animals with higher weights in less time than previously, resulting in more profit per hectare from the farm and a Total Organic Carbon (TOC) increase of between 2-3 times over the period of the project.
kv.label1: total organic carbon, percent, 2012-15

By contrast, the part of the pasture turned into arable ground lost carbon, going from 2.7% organic matter to 1.6% over the same period, a 41% loss. See p. 42 of the (http://www.rothamsted.ac.uk/resources/LongTermExperiments.pdf) Long Term Experiment publication by Rothamsted.

kv.description: This post shows subsidence of peatlands in the English fens south of Peterborough. The top of the post indicates ground level in the 1850s. This is now the lowest land in Britain, with sea level approximately at the level of the collar to which the guy wires are attached. The subsidence of peat, which is mostly carbon-rich organic matter, is mainly due to microbial oxidation as a result of drainage and/or tillage. (http://www.emgs.org.uk/files/local_geology/15%281%29_holme_post.pdf) Paper on peat subsidence near Holme Post
kv.label1: cm of peat per year

kv.description: Ecology 74(2), March 1993, 583-598 reports on the 5-year sandbox experiment at the Hubbard Brook Experimental Forest in New Hampshire. Sandboxes, or lined pits filled with homogenized soil, sand, and topsoil, were planted with a variety of tree species, primarily in order to assess nitrogen fixation. One sandbox was kept unvegetated, and it lost 4 tons per ha per yr of soil organic matter, or 2 T C if we assume that soil organic matter is 50% carbon by weight. Sandboxes planted with red or pitch pine seedlings lost half that, or 1 T C per ha per yr. The study concluded that nitrogen deposition or leaching was unimportant compared to biological nitrogen fixation.
kv.label1: tons C per ha per yr

kv.description: Journal of Environmental Quality39:799-809, May June 2010 reports that at the USDA's Northern Great Plains Research Lab near Mandan, North Dakota, grazing treatments were established in 1916 on western wheatgrass and blue grama pastures. In 1932, they seeded crested wheatgrass into plowed native range. In 1959, soil samples were taken and archived for two native pastures and the crested wheatgrass seeding. In 2003, 44 years later, soils were sampled again with a hydraulic probe at multiple locations within each pasture. All pastures were grazed from May to October with yearling steers: one pasture with .39 animals per hectare, another with 1.1, and the crested wheatgrass seeding was grazed with .4 animals per hectare in spring and early summer, and 2.3 animals per hectare for the remainder of the grazing season. Over 44 years, the more heavily grazed native pasture's measured soil organic carbon content went from 117 tons C per hectare to 135 tons to a depth of about 60 cm, about .41 tons C per hectare per year. The more lightly grazed native grass pasture gained .39 tons C per hectare per year, and the crested wheat seeding gained .46 tons C per hectare per year. This study recorded substantial soil carbon gains over a generation or two, on all three pastures, under season-long grazing. In addition, the researchers measured the flux of methane and nitrous oxide to and from soils, from 2003 to 2006. Soils in all three pastures were found to be sinks for methane, that is, they absorbed more methane than they released, with the greatest absorption occurring in the growing season (presumably due to the activity of methanotrophic bacteria in the soil). Soils in all three pastures were minor to moderate sources of nitrous oxide, with the crested wheatgrass seeding a moderate emitter because of artificial N being applied.
kv.label1: tons C per ha per yr

kv.description: On mixed-grass Wyoming rangeland, heavy grazing (.56 steers per ha, continuous grazing, about 135% of recommended U.S. Dept. of Agriculture-NRCS stocking rate) accumulated around 13 tons of carbon per hectare in comparison to the exclosure, over a 12-year period. 'We found that 12 yr of livestock grazing, after >40 yr of exclusion of both fire and livestock, resulted in a significant increase in the masses of soil C and N in the root zone (0-30 cm) of the soil profile.' Using standard U.S. Environmental Protection Agency figures for enteric methane from cattle, this trial's soil carbon accrual exceeded probable year-round methane output by the .56 steers per hectare by a factor of four, in carbon dioxide equivalent. (http://arsserv0.tamu.edu/SP2UserFiles/Place/54090000/ReederPDF/schuman188_1999%20Ecological%20Applications.pdf) Ecological Applications 9(1), 1999, 65-71

kv.description: An article titled 'The Myth of Nitrogen Fertilization for Soil Carbon Sequestration' ((http://www.fixingourfood.com/pdffiles/Khan_J_Env_Quality_20071.pdf) J. Environ. Qual. 36:1821-1832 [2007]) reports a study at the University of Illinois Morrow Plots, agricultural experiment plots established in 1876. Corn-oats-hay  and corn-oats-soybean rotations recorded a net gain in soil organic carbon in the top 15 cm when fertilized with manure before 1967, and a net loss of soil organic carbon after the switch to synthetic nitrogen fertilization. The paper concludes, 'A half century of synthetic nitrogen fertilization has played a crucial role in expanding worldwide grain production, but there has been a hidden cost to the soil resource: a net loss of native soil organic carbon and the residue carbon inputs.'

kv.description: A 14-year trial of conventional tillage vs. no till growing corn, wheat, and cotton in South Carolina measured an increase of soil carbon in the top 5 cm from .55% to 1.4% under no-till, with no increase with the conventional till. 'The crop residue additions were sufficient for increased C content of a sandy surface soil when surface tillage was absent . . . our data also show that row crop residue production was not sufficient to increase C under conventional tillage.' The most significant carbon increases in the no-till plot were in the surface layers. (http://afrsweb.usda.gov/SP2UserFiles/Place/66570000/Manuscripts/1996/Man414.pdf) Hunt, Karlen, Matheny, and Quisenberry in J. Soil and Water Cons. 51(3) 255-58

kv.description: Rodale Institute's Farming Systems Trial is the longest-running side-by-side comparison of organic and conventional farming systems in the U.S. The results of this trial confirm the potential of organic agricultural practices to grow soil carbon. In the Compost Utilization Trial, the organic plots were amended with compost and/or manure. The best results were obtained with use of composted manure and cover crops. By contrast, the plots under standard tillage with chemical fertilizers lost about a third of a ton of C per hectare per year. Regenerative Organic Farming: A solution to global warming (http://www.donlotter.net/CSU_CUT_Compost.pdf) Compost Science & Utilization, (2009), Vol. 17, No. 2, 117-126
kv.label1: tons C per ha per yr

kv.description: (http://www.asmr.us/Publications/Conference%20Proceedings/2003/2003%20abstracts.pdf) A paper presented at a 2003 Land Reclamation Symposium in Billings, MT reports on a coal mine reclamation. Soil stockpiled for 14 years was respread, mulched, and reseeded, and researchers took soil samples to 15 cm depth. These samples averaged 1.09% organic carbon (Walkley-Black test), and 19 years later they averaged 2.05%, a 3.4% annual increase. Neighboring undisturbed soils remained at about 1.5% organic carbon throughout, making coal dust an unlikely source for the carbon accumulation.

kv.description: In the California Delta, a freshwater tidal marsh thick with tules and other marsh vegetation formed carbon-rich peat soils 60 feet deep in places. In the 1870s, farmers began to build dikes, drain the marshes, burn the tules, and farm the peat soils, which oxidized rapidly on exposure to air. The soil surface descended below sea level, sometimes by inches per year. The levees were reinforced, and the water table lowered some more by pumping, so that farming could continue. By the 1990s the soil surface on some of these peat lands was down to 15, 20, and even 25 feet below sea level. The biological crater left by the oxidation of peat soils in the Delta is about the size of the debris flow from the eruption of Mount St. Helens in 1980. The carbon loss was probably on the order of 10 tons per hectare per year. About ten years ago the US Geological Survey began a small experiment to see if this loss due to oxidation could be reversed. On Twitchell Island, about 15 feet below sea level, they flooded about 6 hectares shallowly, and put in some clumps of tules and cattails. As the plants grew, they raised the water level. After ten years, this experiment has built two feet of peat soils that you can stand on. The plants drew carbon dioxide from the air in photosynthesis, and built complex carbon compounds. The partially decayed dead stalks and roots, protected from further oxidation by careful management of the near-stagnant water, became organic matter or peat. More carbon went in than out. (http://repositories.cdlib.org/jmie/sfews/vol6/iss3/art1/) San Francisco Estuary and Watershed Science, 6(3) (2008) (http://ca.water.usgs.gov/news/carbon_briefing.pdf) USGS summary
kv.label1: tons C per ha per yr

kv.observer: Blain Hjertaas, Peter Donovan, Trent Walls

kv.description: (http://ca.water.usgs.gov/archive/reports/fs00500/fs00500.pdf) This USGS article summarizes the history of subsidence (due mainly to the oxidation of organic peat soils) in the California Delta. According to (http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1672/08-97.1?journalCode=wetl) The Legacy of Wetland Drainage on the Remaining Peat in the Sacramento-San Joaquin Delta, California, USA, the rates of peat loss in the most subsided Delta farmlands reached 11.7 cm (4.6 inches) per year. This point is 19 feet below mean sea level according to Google Earth data.
kv.label1: cm of peat per year

kv.description: Westwind Farm is a hill farm that finishes steers on grass-clover pastures. Two-inch soil samples were measured for organic matter. In 2002, the pastures averaged 4.1% organic matter. In 2007, the average was 8.3%. The estimated tonnage was 1.85 T C per ha per yr, or about 3 tons CO2per acre per yr. According to an (http://soilcarboncoalition.org/holdridge) article in the Grassfed Gazette: 'During 1987-2007, we applied no chemical fertilizers, herbicides, or pesticides. We believe this policy increases the biological life in the soil and increases the rate of carbon sequestration. All manure was deposited in the pastures, thus minimizing methane emissions. For nitrogen we relied on clover, minimizing the formation and emission of nitrous oxide. Furthermore, according to the British Institute of Grassland and Environmental Research (as reported in (http://stockmangrassfarmer.net) Stockman Grass Farmer, May 2008), 'Incorporation of legumes into a pasture would dramatically cut methane emissions.' (Probably that means methane emissions from enteric fermentation.) 'During 2000-2008, we practiced daily rotational grazing on our best pastures and two to three day rotations on lesser pastures. Thus we had a pulsing effect with each rotation, utilizing photosynthesis to pull CO2 into the plant and then into the roots, which partially died following each rotation, leaving decaying roots that became organic matter.' (http://www.westwindfarm.biz) West Wind Farm website
kv.label1: percent per year in top 5 cm

kv.description: As reported in (http://www.researchgate.net/publication/272376062_Tillage_and_Cover_Cropping_Affect_Crop_Yields_and_Soil_Carbon_in_the_San_Joaquin_Valley_California) Agronomy Journal (01/2015; DOI: 10.2134/agronj14.0415), reduced tillage with cover cropping trials with cotton and tomatoes in the San Joaquin valley resulted in increased soil carbon in the top 30 cm from 1999 to 2007. Conventional till and no cover cropping also showed slight increases.
kv.label1: tons C per ha per yr

kv.description: (http://www.chinaflux.org:8080/tmp/SUM-Fu.pdf) Soil Use and Management, 2001(17): 294-96 reports that soil sampling in 1980, and again in same locations in 1999, showed significant increases in soil carbon to 20 cm depth. Grassland to forest samples showed an increase from 1.06% organic matter to 2.28%, an increase of 4.1% per year over 19 years. Samples in farmland that had become grassland showed an increase from 1.05% to 1.45% organic matter, and farmland to forest showed 1.15 to 1.39% organic matter. The authors credit the increase in forest land to the Household Responsibility System, a land reform begun in 1979 which gave land rights to individual farmers. The map location is approximate.

kv.photodescription: After a very heavy rain on June 30-July 1 2017, this culvert on Buzzell Bridge road failed, and you're looking at several hundred yards of the road washed out to a depth of six feet or so. The failure of this culvert may have resulted in part from the failure of another driveway culvert above this. The photo shows that this road was unable to withstand the erosive power of moving water, while the forest on either side was able to do so.

kv.general_observations: Very low diversity.  Orchard grass predominates.
kv.site_description: This is a ~12 acre hay field that receives horse manure spread on it daily, Nov-April, every year since 2010. Seeding has not occurred for several years. Almost a monoculture of Orchard Grass at this point. Area is flat.The field gets cut 2 times per year with a yield of 450-520 bales per year with most recent years seeing steady increase. The annual amount of manure spread is ~700 tons, which equates to almost 10 tons per month (during the ~6 month period) per acre. Some Seldan Spray is used as a spot spray against broadleaf plants once or twice per year.

kv.subject: Hay bale production over the years
kv.comment: Walnut Creek Stables gave us 8 years of hay bale production for this 12 acre site starting from 2010. While we have #bales, we do not have tons of composted horse manure/bedding for the first 7 years.  In 2010 they did 2 cuttings yielding 699 bales. 2011, 2 cuttings for total of 500 bales. 2012, 2 cuttings for total of 521 bales. 2013, 2 cuttings for total of 445 bales. 2014 and 2015 were "dry" and yielded (2 cuttings each year) 491 and 358 bales respectively. 2016, 2 cuttings for total of 469 bales.  A "Production Observation" was entered for 2017 which specified that the yield was 520 bales and the input was 700 tons of composted horse manure and bedding.

kv.site_description: Higher level above water channel by sycamore to the east, alkali sacaton patch. Before Lake Kaweah dam (1961) this alkali meadow area would flood seasonally. Deep Creek to the north saw no water during drought years. Never been farmed, grazed for 100 years? The Nature Conservancy made it a preserve in 1983, conservation targets were valley oak woodland and alkali meadow. TNC stopped grazing at least for a while, particularly in woodland areas. Since 2005 rotational grazing among pastures, sometimes for entire year.

kv.description: Retired from irrigation. Moist soils from recent ditch overflow, some surface cracks. In pomegranates for 7 years, row crops before that, seeded with bearded wheat and grasses winter 2016-2017, cut for silage, grazed by sheep.

kv.general_observations: Annual ryegrass, groundcherry, knotweed, barnyard grass, pomegranate sprouts, russian thistle sprouts, clover--vegatation patchy and not well distributed. About half or more of land is bare here. Moist soil from recent wetting from ditch leakage, clay soil has surface cracks. Soil samples in 4 x 4m plot show high variability in terms of clay color: dark with yellow streaks, blue streaks, some of the yellowish clay has orange mottles, plus some very sandy pockets. Because of visible variability of soil cores, this site may not be best for measuring soil change over time.

kv.subject: Haney Info diff betwn soil tests
kv.comment:
From: Lance Gunderson <Lgunderson@wardlab.com>
Date: June 11, 2018 at 12:34:41 PM EDT
To: "Holly.Utrata-Halcomb@hamilton-co.org" <Holly.Utrata-Halcomb@hamilton-co.org>
Subject: Re: Haney Info
Hi Holly, 

I too am confused by what I am looking at in more ways than one.  First, the P test from MSU is done using a Bray 1 extraction, so this P value would be even higher if they used a Mehlich 3 extraction, which the H3A from the Haney Test has been correlated to.  The second confusing part of this is that they are recommending additional P be applied and you should have ample P available at those test levels.  They are also requesting a lot of N, but I don't see a soil test level for N evaluated on their report so I don't know how they are determining how much N you need to apply unless they are simply assuming no N in your soil to start with.  

When I convert Mg from the Haney Test I get a value of 354, which is pretty close to the value they give you for 388.  I take the 186 * 1.4281 + 88.197 to get 354.  K is a little different.  Your test result on the Haney test is pretty low at 32, which converted is about 82, a little more than half of what they measured at MSU.  At a value of 32 we are getting pretty low on our calibration curve.  We don't normally see samples read quite that low and our conversion is likely a little better when we start with values around 100 up to 200 or so.  Above 200 on the Haney Test and we don't recommend K.  For Ca we stared with 1024 ppm on the Haney test, which equates to 2466 ppm using the conversion equation.  This actually isn't too bad for a comparison with the 2094 you got from MSU.  

Again, P is the biggest difference I see here.  As part of the Haney Test we evaluate P on 2 different extracts (you only see the H3A value, but the other is a water extract) using 2 different sets of calibration standards and 2 different pieces of analytical equipment.  Both the Lachat, which measures H3A extractable inorganic P, and the ICAP, which measures total H3A extractable P, gave us much lower numbers than what is reported by MSU.  

If we still have the sample, I am going to re-run the P portion of the test to double check our numbers and I will do this at no additional charge.  Hopefully, we still have the sample, and if so, I will be in touch when we have some more values for the re-runs. 

Thanks, 
Lance

Hi Holly, 
 
Yes, some of the nutrients match up better than others.  This is why we don't normally recommend using the Haney Test for making decisions regarding micronutrient applications at this time.  The test was designed to look at water extractable organic C and N fraction coupled with respiration to give us a better idea of microbial function and nutrient cycling abilities of your soil as it relates to soil health.  However, some individuals wanted to start seeing some of the other nutrient values using an H3A extract so we can start to build up a database and to make comparisons with more conventional extracts.  Rick a lot of this work, but much of his focus was on NPK when it came to the plant nutrient side of things.

kv.comment:
continuation of last comment:

Lance,
Thank you for your assessment. The Michigan test did not recommend more P. It has been explained to me by the MSU soil Lab Manager, John Dahl, that they do not test for any form of N because it is too volatile. By the time the customer receives the results, the N value would have changed. So, I believe you are correct, they assume there is no N. 

Our limestone/shale parent material cause our soils to have a higher pH, high P and low K. It is very common for us to also have high Mg and Ca.  I’ll be interested to learn what your second test for P reveals.
Thank you for your interest.
Holly

kv.subject: continuation of P discussion
kv.comment:
Lance Gunderson <Lgunderson@wardlab.com>
Hi Holly, 

Sorry, I see now that the rec values on the MSU report were adjusted to show no additional P needed.  

We have completed the re-runs of your sample (#599 Hamilton) and here are the results. 

Inorganic H3A P: 4.79

Total H3A ICAP P: 8.74

H3A ICAP K: 37.11

H3A ICAP Mg: 183.4

I also elected to run Bray P1 on this sample just so we could compare apples to apples with the P value on the MSU report.  The Bray P1 value we got was 7.22, which is what we would expect when comparing it to the H3A P values.  

The Bray P1 and H3A values for P were run by different technicians using different instruments (both were Lachat FIA analyzers, but 2 different machines).  

Thanks, 
Lance

kv.unit1:
1-day CO2-C:
National 4 year average is 52 ppm
This result is one of the most important numbers in the soil test procedure. This value is the amount of CO2-C (ppm) released in 24 hr. from soil microbes after your soil has been dried and rewetted (as occurs naturally in the field). This is a measurement of the microbial activity in the soil and is highly related to soil fertility. In most cases, the higher the number, the more fertile the soil.
kv.sampleID: Soil Carbon Coalition BORP1 CA-15591-R  Haney Lab
kv.unit2:
Soil Health Calculation:
National 4 year average is 9.3
This number is calculated as 1-day CO2-C / 10 + WEOC/100 + WEON/10 to include a weighted contribution of microbial activity, water extractable organic C and N. It represents the overall health of your soil system. It combines 5 independent measurements of your soil’s biological and chemical properties. The calculation looks at the balance of soil C and N and their relationship to microbial activity. This soil health calculation number can vary from 0 to more than 50. We like to see this number increase over time. This number indicates the current soil health and helps us identify what it needs to reach its highest sustainable state. Keeping track of this Soil Health number will allow you to gauge the effects of your management practices over the years.
